SystemD is the service manager responsible for booting the system, managing and monitoring services, managing logs through Journald 


Core commands:
Systemctl status <service>        (checks service status) 
Systemctl start <service>         (starts service) 
Systemctl stop <service>          (stops service) 
Systemctl restart <service>       (restarts service) 
systemctl enable <service>        (enables service on boot) 
systemctl disable <service>       (disables service on boot) 
systemctl daemon-reload           (tells systemd to read new unit files/service) 

A systemD unit file describes how a service is run 
Dependancies: Required (HARD) Wants (Soft) After (Ordering) 


SystemD has many unit types like: 
.service    (Managed by Daemon) 
.target		(Boot stages) 
.timer		(Scheduled tasks) 
.mount		(Filesystem mountpoint) 
.socket		(Networking) 